 M http://src.chromium.org/viewvc/chrome/trunk/src/native_client/src/trusted/service_runtime/testdata/x86_64/fib_scalar.nexe?r1=4116&amp;r2=4115&amp;pathrev=4116
 M http://src.chromium.org/viewvc/chrome/trunk/src/native_client/src/trusted/service_runtime/testdata/x86_32/fib_scalar.nexe?r1=4116&amp;r2=4115&amp;pathrev=4116

change off_t and ino_t to 64-bits.  as a consequence, the size of the
stat structure has also increased.  furthermore, our x86-64 syscall
convention only deals with 32-bit values (since we're ILP32), and
since the ABI for lseek and mmap took immediate off_t arguments (as
opposed to by reference, as stat/fstat), the syscall ABI didn't work;
rather than changing the x86-64 syscall ABI to use 64-bit values, this
CL changes lseek and mmap syscalls to take a pointer to the offset --
which is a 32-bit value.


